Comment:
A running gag throughout the series is Plankton's many attempts to obtain the Krabby Patty formula as a means to attract customers to his restaurant, the Chum Bucket, usually through disguise and deceit. All of said attempts have failed, usually ending with Mr. Krabs throwing him back to the Chum Bucket or snatching the bottle out of his hands. 
The secret formula plays an essential role in the plotlines for the two movies adaptations of the series. In them, Plankton devises numerous ways to steal the formula as he does in many episodes in the series. In the second movie, it is Burger-Beard the Pirate who attempts and succeeds to steal the secret formula in order to set up his own fast-food business on land.

Title: The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water Official Trailer #1 (2015) - Animated Movie HD
Comment:
To all of the people who doubt this movie. Here's why I think it's going to be good: 

1.) Stephen Hillenburg is heavily involved and will be returning to the series in Season 10

2.) The bad writers like Zeus Cervas and Casey Alexander have nothing to do with this movie, they have the writers from Kung Fu Panda

3.) The CGI actually doesn't look that bad, and it's mostly going to be in 2D animation. We should be grateful that there's at least some 2D in it. 

4.) The Superhero plot only looks like its going to be in the climax, so it probably won't be long. But it might surprise us all.

5.) Most Importantly, EVERYONE IS IN CHARACTER, Patrick isn't a prick, Squidward hasn't been tortured, Sandy isn't obsessed with science, Mr. Krabs isn't a criminal, and Spongbob isn't an annoying stalker. I feel like I'm watching genuine Spongebob again. Even the haters can agree with me on this one.

Comment: According to CartoonBrew, the film will have CGI characters near the climax. Mostly it will stick with the 2D animation. If this is true, then Paramount Animation may be the only major US studio that is flying the flag for 2D animation, since most major studios don't do 2D, probably because 1. they want to compete with video games. 2. there are tax incentives in other states except California. 3. they think that 2D doesn't make money. This is why they're marketing quite heavily on the CGI, since they may be embarrassed to have a bomb on their hands. I'm a big fan of 2D animation, and I feel there are things about 2D (even if you create it in the computer) that need to be explored. It's difficult right now for me to get my animation studio started because of more important matters related to school, but after we make our first show, we'll do two short films. One in traditional 2D, and one in 3D CGI. The place where I live, GA, is a really good place to do this, even though most film activity that takes place in GA is live action.
